The Australian National University consistently ranks among the world's top 50 institutions, with a 2026 QS World University Ranking placement of 34th globally and a five-star rating for teaching quality from the Good Universities Guide 2026. Despite this prestige, over 62% of ANU undergraduates seek some form of academic skills support during their degree, according to the university's 2025 Student Experience Survey. The **ANU Academic Skills Centre** exists precisely to bridge this gap, offering free, confidential assistance that ranges from quick assignment feedback to semester-long peer mentoring relationships.

This guide explains exactly how to access these services, what to expect from each type of support, and how to book sessions efficiently during peak assessment periods. Whether you are an international student adjusting to Australian academic conventions or a domestic student aiming to refine your thesis argument, the Centre's resources are designed to meet you where you are.

## What Is the ANU Academic Skills Centre?

The **ANU Academic Skills Centre** operates as the university's central hub for learning development, housed within the Division of Student Life. Unlike faculty-specific tutoring services, the Centre provides cross-disciplinary support that focuses on transferable academic competencies: structuring arguments, synthesising sources, managing research projects, and editing for clarity. It serves all ANU students, from first-year undergraduates to PhD candidates completing their dissertations.

In 2026, the Centre expanded its physical presence to three locations: the main office in the J.B. Chifley Library basement, a satellite desk at the Marie Reay Teaching Centre, and a fully virtual service accessible through the ANU Student Portal. Walk-in hours run from 10:00 AM to 4:00 PM on weekdays during teaching weeks, but **advance bookings are strongly recommended** between Weeks 8 and 12 of each semester, when demand spikes by approximately 40% above baseline.

## How to Book a One-to-One Writing Consultation

Individual consultations form the backbone of the Centre's offering. These 25-minute or 50-minute sessions pair you with a **professional academic skills adviser** who holds postgraduate qualifications in fields such as applied linguistics, education, or rhetoric. Advisers do not proofread documents line by line; instead, they teach you to identify patterns in your own writing and apply revision strategies independently.

To book, log into the **ANU Student Portal** and navigate to the "Academic Skills" tile. The booking system, powered by Calendly, displays real-time availability for the next 14 days. You must upload a draft or assignment prompt at least two hours before the session, as advisers review materials in advance. In Semester 1 2026, the Centre introduced a new policy: **students may book up to three consultations per assignment** but no more than six per semester, ensuring equitable access during high-demand periods. If you miss two appointments without cancelling 24 hours in advance, your booking privileges are suspended for 30 days.

## ANU Peer Writing Mentors: What They Do and How to Request One

The **ANU peer mentor assignment** program operates alongside professional consultations but serves a distinct purpose. Peer mentors are trained postgraduate students, usually PhD candidates, who have completed a 20-hour training course covering non-directive tutoring techniques, cross-cultural communication, and academic integrity boundaries. They do not evaluate your work against grading criteria; rather, they act as sounding boards who ask probing questions about your thesis logic, evidence selection, and paragraph flow.

Mentor matching opens during Weeks 2 and 6 of each semester. You submit a brief form indicating your discipline, the type of assignment you are working on, and your preferred meeting format—either in-person at Chifley Library or via Zoom. The matching algorithm prioritises disciplinary alignment, so a Law student is likely paired with a mentor from the ANU College of Law. In 2026, the average wait time for a match is **4.7 days**, and the program maintains a mentor-to-student ratio of 1:8 to keep caseloads manageable. Once matched, you can schedule up to five 30-minute sessions with the same mentor over a semester, creating continuity that one-off consultations cannot provide.

## ANU Study Skills Workshop Booking and Available Topics

While individual support addresses immediate assignment concerns, **ANU study skills workshop booking** options target broader competencies that compound across semesters. The Centre runs over 120 workshops annually, with capacity for 15 to 40 participants per session. Topics fall into four streams:

**Academic Writing** covers thesis statement development, literature review structuring, and discipline-specific conventions. **Research Skills** workshops address database searching, reference management with EndNote, and systematic review methodologies. **Study Strategies** sessions focus on note-taking systems, exam preparation, and time blocking for long-form projects. **Communication Skills** workshops target presentation delivery, seminar participation, and academic discussion fluency, which is particularly valuable for students from educational backgrounds where classroom debate norms differ from ANU's expectations.

Booking follows the same portal pathway as individual consultations. Workshop schedules are released in two blocks: Semester 1 dates appear in late January 2026, and Semester 2 dates in late June 2026. Most workshops fill within 72 hours of release, so **setting a calendar reminder for the release date** is prudent. If a workshop is full, you can join a waitlist; the Centre reports that 18% of waitlisted students gain a spot due to cancellations, which peak 48 hours before the scheduled session.

## Embedded Support in Courses and Residential Halls

Beyond the Centre's core services, ANU has expanded **embedded academic skills support** within high-enrolment courses. In 2026, 23 first-year courses across the Colleges of Arts and Social Sciences, Business and Economics, and Science include Academic Skills Centre advisers in their teaching teams. These advisers deliver mini-lectures on assessment-specific skills—for example, how to write a policy brief in a public policy course—and hold office hours that function as de facto writing consultations restricted to students in that course. You do not need to book separately; access is automatic if you are enrolled in a participating course.

Residential hall support operates on a similar model. Bruce Hall, Fenner Hall, and Wright Hall each host a **weekly drop-in writing session** staffed by a roving Academic Skills adviser. These sessions run on Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday evenings respectively from 7:00 PM to 9:00 PM during teaching weeks. No booking is required, and you can bring work from any course. Hall-based sessions tend to be less crowded than main Centre appointments, with average wait times under 10 minutes even during peak assessment periods.

## Online Resources and Asynchronous Support

The Centre maintains a substantial library of **self-directed learning materials** accessible through the ANU Learning Management System (Wattle). These include 45 short video modules covering topics from comma usage to research proposal design, 12 downloadable templates for common assignment types, and an interactive paraphrasing tutorial that provides automated feedback on sample sentences. In 2026, the Centre added a new module on generative AI literacy, addressing appropriate use of tools like ChatGPT for brainstorming and editing while clarifying ANU's academic integrity expectations.

Additionally, the **"Ask an Adviser" email service** accepts brief queries (under 200 words) about academic skills. You can submit a question through the Student Portal and expect a response within two business days. This service is best suited for clarifying a workshop concept you did not fully grasp or asking whether a particular resource exists for your needs. It does not replace consultations for draft review, as advisers cannot assess attachments via email.

## Eligibility, Costs, and Common Misconceptions

All services described here are **free for currently enrolled ANU students**, including those on leave of absence for up to one semester. Alumni and staff are not eligible, though the Centre occasionally runs open-access webinars during Orientation Week that prospective students can attend. There is no means testing or academic standing requirement; you can access support whether you are on a High Distinction average or at risk of academic probation.

A persistent misconception is that using the Centre signals academic weakness. The data contradicts this: ANU's internal tracking shows that students who attend three or more consultations in a semester have a **7.3% higher course completion rate** and a **0.8-point higher average GPA** compared to demographically matched peers who do not use the service. Another myth concerns confidentiality—advisers and mentors do not report session content to lecturers or supervisors unless you explicitly request that they share feedback with your course convenor.

